{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MCLExtVtre8mae32WQ5Ztd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed — unchanged files are not scanned.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This behavior involves getting the list of changed files from GitHub API/git diff and filtering which files to analyze. The failure mode is about the file selection logic — does it correctly identify changed files?\n- REAL-INFRA: Getting the list of changed files could be done via GitHub API or git commands. If this is tested with a fake/mock list of changed files, we can test the filtering logic. But the actual file list comes from GitHub API or subprocess git calls.\n\n\n- MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the GitHub API or git call lets us test the filtering logic in isolation, but the real failure mode is whether the system correctly fetches changed files from GitHub and only analyzes those. The core issue is whether we're properly identifying which files are \"changed\" — this requires either hitting GitHub's API or running git commands to get the actual list, then filtering to only scan those files.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM involved.\n- MULTI-STEP: No multiple agentic steps.\n\nSince this is a GitHub Action running in a real environment, we could mock the GitHub API response and verify that only those files get scanned, treating it as an integration test between the \"get changed files\" module and the \"analyze files\" module. The key question is whether the system correctly identifies and filters changed files — that's where the failure would surface.\n\nNow looking at the second behavior about grouping findings by severity in the PR comment — this is purely formatting and grouping logic, so the failure modes would be in how the results are organized and displayed.\n\nThe key question is whether we need the real GitHub API to verify this works. We don't, since we can mock the post call and just check that the content being sent has the correct grouping. So this could be tested at the Unit level for the grouping logic itself, or Integration if we want to verify the full pipeline produces the right output format.\n\nFor the timeout behavior with 200 files, this is inherently a performance test that only fails under load, so we can't catch it with a small dataset.  Real filesystem I/O and subprocess execution timing in the GitHub Actions environment are what matter here — mocking those away would hide the actual bottleneck. This has to run at the System level.\n\nFor behavior 4, I'm starting to analyze the crash-recovery scenario...\n\nThe core question is whether a subprocess crash requires real subprocess behavior to test properly. A malformed file causing the linter to crash is fundamentally about subprocess exit codes and signal handling — not something that mocking can reliably capture. The failure mode is whether the system continues processing remaining files after a subprocess crash, which demands real subprocess behavior to validate correctly. The subprocess crash behavior is explicitly about real process failure, so mocking might mask signal handling issues — this needs to stay at System level. For the deduplication behavior, it's pure algorithmic logic with no external dependencies, so that's clearly Unit. Now I'm mapping out the test levels for each behavior: the file filtering is Integration, and I'm working through the remaining findings to determine their classification. Workflow: 0.02\n\nFor handling 200 files within the timeout, that's clearly a system-level concern at 0.80 probability since it requires actual execution timing. Linter crashes that allow continued processing also lean heavily toward system tests at 0.65. Deduplication logic, though, is straightforward enough to be mostly unit-testable at 0.80.\n\nLooking back at the first behavior more carefully—analyzing only changed files—I need to think through what's actually involved. Getting that list of changed files requires some mechanism to fetch them, whether through GitHub's API or git commands.  Then there's the filtering logic and running analysis only on those files. In a GitHub Actions context, this could come from environment variables that GitHub sets, which would be a system dependency, or from an API call, also system-level. But I could test this with a mock by injecting a list of changed files alongside some unchanged ones and verifying only the changed ones get analyzed—that's integration-level testing. The minimum to catch failures is just that: provide the file list and verify the filtering works correctly. I'll keep integration as the baseline with system having meaningful probability since the actual file retrieval mechanism could fail independently.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10086,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10086},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e5871cae-295b-4442-b02c-61d1860bf7a8","uuid":"45be948e-9e1a-4cd2-8793-d4a0eabfcc5f"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MCLExtVtre8mae32WQ5Ztd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019YNenDQyKG4yAJHBvbFz3k","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed — unchanged files are not scanned.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure boundary is the handoff between 'fetch changed file list' (GitHub API or git subprocess) and 'select files to analyze.' A pure unit test of the filter function alone cannot catch a bug where the wrong list is fetched or the integration between fetch and filter is broken. REAL-INFRA: The changed-file list can be injected via a stub HTTP client or mock git response without needing a real GitHub API call — an in-process fake reproduces the failure. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the file-fetch call still lets us verify the filter logic consumes the list correctly; the core failure mode (analyzing unchanged files) is visible with a stub. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network required — stub HTTP response reproduces the failure. (b) No AI/ML. (c) No multi-step agentic chain. EVIDENCE-LEVEL: Integration. OUTPUT-LEVEL: Integration. No override.","test_description":"Wire the file-fetch module (stubbed to return a known set of 'changed' files) to the analysis dispatcher. Place both changed and unchanged files on a fake filesystem. Assert the analysis module receives exactly the stubbed changed-file list and no unchanged-file paths appear in the findings or scan log.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.27,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Findings are grouped by severity (error, warning, info) in the posted PR comment.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure can appear either in the grouping algorithm or in the serialization path that renders grouped findings into the comment body. A unit test of the grouping function alone misses bugs where the grouped data is flattened or re-sorted before posting. The failure boundary spans grouping → formatting → HTTP POST payload. REAL-INFRA: A stub HTTP client can capture the exact comment body POSTed to GitHub without a real API call; in-process fakes fully reproduce the failure. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking only at the HTTP layer still lets us assert the payload contains the correct severity sections. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real network required. (b) No AI/ML. (c) No multi-step chain. EVIDENCE-LEVEL: Integration. OUTPUT-LEVEL: Integration. No override.","test_description":"Inject a synthetic findings list with mixed severities into the full pipeline (grouper → formatter → HTTP poster with a stub client). Capture the comment body sent to the stub. Assert it contains distinct sections for 'error,' 'warning,' and 'info,' each containing only the correctly-severity-matched findings.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.57,"System":0.21,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A pull request that touches 200 files completes analysis within the 10-minute Actions timeout.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Timing failure only surfaces under real execution conditions — process startup overhead, real filesystem I/O across 200 files, and real subprocess invocations per file all contribute to wall-clock time. REAL-INFRA: An in-process mock of file reads or subprocess calls removes the actual I/O cost, making any timing assertion meaningless. The failure mode (exceeding 10 minutes) only appears with real subprocess execution and real filesystem access. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking subprocess.run hides the dominant cost (linter process startup × 200); the test would always pass regardless of actual performance. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) Yes — real subprocess execution time and real filesystem I/O are required to observe the failure; demoting to Integration would hide the bottleneck. REJECTION-GATE: No text in the behavior disqualifies System; 'within the 10-minute Actions timeout' explicitly references real execution wall time. EVIDENCE-LEVEL: System. OUTPUT-LEVEL: System. No override.","test_description":"Create 200 synthetic source files on a real (or tmpfs) filesystem. Invoke the Action step as a real subprocess with a wall-clock timer. Assert total elapsed time is under 600 seconds. Optionally set a stricter soft budget (e.g., 300s) to catch regressions before they breach the hard limit.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.83,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the linter process crashes on a malformed file, the remaining files are still analyzed and results posted.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure boundary is process-level crash recovery: does the driver loop correctly detect a non-zero exit code or signal termination from the linter subprocess and continue with the next file? REAL-INFRA: A real subprocess crash (non-zero exit, segfault signal, or unhandled exception) exercises OS-level process management that in-process mocks cannot replicate — mocking subprocess.run to raise an exception is a different failure mode than a real crash exit code. MOCK-HIDE: Replacing the linter with a mock that raises a Python exception hides real behavior: crash cleanup, partial output on stdout/stderr, exit-code parsing, and signal propagation all differ from an in-process exception. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) Yes — 'linter process crashes' is explicitly a subprocess crash; real subprocess behavior is required to observe the exact failure mode. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior text says 'linter process crashes' — this is a real subprocess event, not an exception within the driver. Cannot disqualify System. EVIDENCE-LEVEL: System. OUTPUT-LEVEL: System. No override.","test_description":"Create a batch of files including one known-malformed file. Supply a real (or minimal test-double) linter binary that exits with code 1 (or SIGSEGV) on the malformed file and exits 0 on all others. Invoke the Action step as a subprocess. Assert the posted comment (captured via stub HTTP or output file) contains findings from all non-malformed files and none are silently dropped.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate findings on the same line from overlapping rules are deduplicated in the output.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Deduplication is a pure algorithmic transformation: given a list of findings (file, line, rule, message), return a list with duplicates removed. The failure lives entirely inside this function — no module handoff, no I/O. REAL-INFRA: No filesystem, network, or subprocess is involved in the deduplication step. MOCK-HIDE: No external dependency needs mocking; the function is self-contained. LLM-DEP: No AI/ML involved. MULTI-STEP: No agentic chain. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No OS/network. (b) No AI/ML. (c) No multi-step chain. EVIDENCE-LEVEL: Unit. OUTPUT-LEVEL: Unit. No override.","test_description":"Construct a synthetic list of findings that includes exact duplicates (same file, same line, same rule) and near-duplicates (same line, different rule). Call the deduplication function directly. Assert the output contains each unique (file, line, rule) tuple exactly once, and that near-duplicates with different rules are preserved as distinct entries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10086,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10086},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e5871cae-295b-4442-b02c-61d1860bf7a8","uuid":"aa4d2146-0344-4d6b-834f-844b5d30c066"}
